pullRequest.body:
Let `K` be a number field of signature `(r‚ÇÅ, r‚ÇÇ)`. This PR defines the fundamental cone: it is a cone in the mixed space that is a fundamental domain for the action of `(ùìû K)À£` modulo torsion. 

In a later PR #12333, we prove that points in the fundamental cone coming from `(ùìû K)` modulo torsion are in a norm-preserving correspondence with the non-zero principal ideals of `(ùìû K)`. 

This PR is part of the proof of the Analytic Class Number Formula.

This can go to `Mathlib.NumberTheory.NumberField.CanonicalEmbedding.Basic` I think.

Yeah, I though about that but it needs a small result from Units.lean and this file imports CanonicalEmbedding/Basic.lean. I guess one way to solve that would be to split Units.lean with basic definitions /results on one part and Dirichlet theorem in the other part. That's probably not such a bad idea, the two parts could to go into a new Unit directory with the file about the regulator too...
Why not. `Units.lean` is already not small, and it will probably became bigger and bigger.
It doesn't matter that much, but can you write this in term mode?
Sure.
Maybe `simp`?
Can you explain where `ofIsReal` as a single unit of the name comes from?
It is coming from the hypothesis that the infinite place is real, that is `InfinitePlace.IsReal`.
Please leave a deprecated alias

I would not use `--` as a dash in lean code 
```suggestion
* `NumberField.mixedEmbedding.fundamentalCone`: a cone in the mixed space‚Äîthat is a subset stable
by multiplication by a real number, see `smul_mem_of_mem`‚Äî, that is also a fundamental domain
```
Yes, you're right. That's probably a recipe for disaster

You can use
```suggestion
  smul u x := (mixedEmbedding K u) * x
```
and also below
I think we start explicit names for instances with `inst`
Not, in these cases I think, see for eg. Submonoid.smul. I guess it's because the simps attribute is gonna create some lemmas and we want those to have "nice" names.
@Ruben-VandeVelde, I created #16762 to split this PR into smaller ones. You can continue the discussion there if you want.
I think I'd expect `unit_smul` in the name rather than `unitSMul` anyway

```suggestion
theorem unitSMul_eq_iff_mul_eq {x y : ùìû K} {u : (ùìû K)À£} :
```

```suggestion
    mul_comm (finrank ‚Ñö K : ‚Ñù) _, mul_assoc, mul_inv_cancel‚ÇÄ (Nat.cast_ne_zero.mpr finrank_pos.ne'),
    mul_one, sub_self, mul_zero, Pi.zero_apply]
```
Oh, nice, I didn't know that existed.

```suggestion
/-- The fundamental cone is a cone in the mixed space‚Äîthat is a subset fixed by multiplication by
a scalar, see `smul_mem_of_mem`‚Äî, that is also a fundamental domain for the action of `(ùìû K)À£` up
```

```suggestion
  lt_of_le_of_ne (mixedEmbedding.norm_nonneg _) (Ne.symm hx.2)
```
Another lemma I didn't know existed. Thanks for the pointer :)

```suggestion
  lt_of_le_of_ne (normAtPlace_nonneg _ _)
    ((mixedEmbedding.norm_ne_zero_iff.mp (norm_pos_of_mem hx).ne' w).symm)
```

```suggestion
    (hŒ∂ : Œ∂ ‚àà torsion K) : Œ∂ ‚Ä¢ x ‚àà fundamentalCone K := by
```

```suggestion
  constructor
```
Just more user friendly.

```suggestion
  refine ‚ü®fun h ‚Ü¶ ?_, fun h ‚Ü¶ torsion_smul_mem_of_mem hx h‚ü©
```
Removing the last line (and fixing the indentation).

```suggestion
  (basisModTorsion K).map (logEmbeddingEquiv K)
```
This and the previous one end with `rfl`. Are we missing some lemmas here?

Yes, it is a bit of a mystery to me. I think we're missing something like `Additive.toMul x = Additive.toMul y ‚Üí x = y` and similar results (whose proofs is essentially `rfl` too) but I am not sure they're worth adding. The mess in `fundSystem_mk` comes also from the fact that there are two kinds of `Additive.toMul` involved...
I have the impression you are abusing defeq: `logEmbedding` takes a term of type `Additive (ùìû K)À£`, but you are giving it `fundSystem K i`, which has type `(ùìû K)À£`. Can we fix this somehow?
Yeah, you're right. I am probably a bit sloppy with my use of `Additive`. I'll see if I can fix that

All right, I think I took of all the abuses of defeq. There was a lot of `Additive.ofMul` missing but also the use `‚ü¶x‚üß` rather than `QuotientGroup.mk x` to go from `(ùìû K)À£` to `((ùìû K)À£ ‚ß∏ (torsion K))` that resulted in a wrongly typed quotient.
You can put `c` and `hc` in the `variable` line.
What happened here?

Well, I was tracking the `defeq` abused but did not finish since I need to prepare my class for tomorrow. I'll put this PR in `WIP` for the time being until I finish.  Thanks for the review and the suggestion to fix the defeq
